  \section Color spaces

  Interpolating colors can be done in various color spaces, with different results. Which color space should be used may depend on the application. There is a quick comparison of different color spaces.

  SRGB: SRGB is the standard color space for common screens. As such, working directly in SRGB has the advantage that it does not require any color conversion to be displayed. Moreover, varying colors intensity linearly in SRGB produce a perceptually nearly linear color gradient. The main drawback is that intermediate colors when interpolating between two bright and saturated colors tend to be too dark.

  Linear RGB or XYZ: Working in a linear color space may be necessary sometimes. For instance, Applying shading on a surface should be done in a linear color space to get good results. It is however not really practical to create color gradient because of the strong non-linearity of human perception.

  Cie Lab: The Lab color space has been designed specifically to be close to human perception. Computing the distance between two colors in Lab should give a good idea of how different the colors are for a human. This color space produce good results to compute diffusion image while avoiding artifacts we have in SRGB. Although Lab conversion is the more expansive, this is the recommended color space to work with diffusion images.

  Keep in mind that to avoid artifacts with Vitelotte, you should compute diffusion and interpolate colors over each face using the same color space. Failing to do so may make the edge more easily noticeable.

